,Recommended,328080,32159088,Posted: 3 June,all,KillParadise,"The dev is an amazing person his energy is what originaly drove me to purchase the game, and now I am pretty addicted to the game itself.The game itself really has a little for everyone in it. (Please note I am playing the latest unstable version)Want to test your metal in managing a city under siege? Survival is for youSurvival too easy? Try NightmareMore of a turtle player like me and want to take your time but still have some threat? Traditional is there for youWant to just play a retro city builder? Peaceful mode is available for you.Being in early access I feel like the content availble in the game is worth the $9.99 to support the dev and its future development, it's enough to keep you entertained and just as you hit the peak a new patch comes out with some new content for you to try.Gameplay is fair you will learn as you go what is needed pronto to keep things stable, the learning curve is pretty high but that adds to the fun imo. (I am still learning food & water management).As for play style you really can choose how you'd like, of course in the harder difficulties the main strategy is to play more like a TD but it's truly in your hands how you play, defense is a major key to your little villagers survival.Overall this game is great to far, the dev is great, gameplay is great, and the content is pretty great too. Keep up the great work!"
76561198049511866,Recommended,328080,29091863,Posted: 7 January,all,rouge1701,"Difficult games fall into two catagories: Those that are challenging, and those that are frustrating.  This game, alas, falls into the later category.My main issues:1.  There is no good way to control overheating in summer.  Especially when the 1200hp Zombie is fighting them all in the middle of the day.  They stand and fight and die of heat exhaustion.2.  The monster difficulty seems to grow exponentially.  On day 3, it's not uncommon for 700 to 800 hp monsters to waltz through my defences.  By day 5, they're close to 1500 hp.  I've never made it past that point, so I can only guess how vastly overpowered they become.3.  The inability to rotate buildings.  When most buildings are rectangles, it helps to compact your base.4.  The monsters just break through the walls, rather than going through the killing maze.  It's impossible to concentrate enough fire when they come through whatever wall is inconvenient to them.5.  What it boils down to is a tower defence game with a focus on the infrastructure behind the towers.  It's not what I was expecting from a village simulator.  I'm not a big fan of tower defence games to begin with, so this was a rather sad realization.6.  There are no guards or soldiers.  You get golems who can't stand a chance against anything but a slime.  It would be nice to have soldiers who could sortie out and soften up the monsters.EDIT:I am changing my review to positive.  The developer is prompt and courteous, and there seems to be a lot of changes in the works.  I kind of forgot the game is in alpha still because of how well it looks and, aside from the frustrations mentioned above, works.I suppose, deep down, I'm afraid of getting burned by another Towns.  Thankfully, I don't think that's a concern here.  I look forward to the continued development of what portends to be a great time waster."
76561198010580253,Recommended,328080,32304591,Posted: 9 June,all,pmm5000,"Tldr: This is a city building tower defense god game that makes time go by far more quickly than you'd like.This game is basically some wierd fusion of city building, tower defence, and god games (you have a floating hand and you can pick stuff up). Now I can't say everyone will enjoy it. Especially since you are basically guarenteed to lose your first few games. However, the reason why you lose, often times will not be the same. I've lost due to starvation, dehydration, lack of defences, overbuilding, stupid lightning storms (this problem was actually solved in a recent update) random monsters appearing in areas I didn't check, random monsters breaking in because my own towers betrayed me by destroying the terrain, and just plain being overran by slimes and zombies. This is one of those games that will cause you to be like, okay, I lost because of this, what can I do to live longer? And this will haunt you till you finally last longer than one year in game. Even then, maybe another year.After that.....I'm sorry, Ray (the developer), there's no real end game. Not yet anyways. Although, for you random people reading this, this game is updated literally every month or two. Opt into unstable releases and you can play a new update roughly every two to three weeks.Also for you complete and total over-achievers, you should try to conquer the map by building fire pits all over it. And then, strip mine it and deforest the land. By this point.....not going to lie, you just spent an entire day or two in the real world questioning, just what did you even do with your life?I swear, every update I spend like 8 hours testing out the new content. I only recently managed to shrink this time by using cheat engine. Which I completely and thoroughly recommend you do. Not because of cheating (which I haven't figured out how to do yet nor feel the need to do) but because there isn't a time warping ability yet. Simply enable the speed hack and you've shrunk the time from 8 hours to 4. Possibly even 3. Well.....I say this, but somehow I still end up playing for 8 hours even though I had it sped up by three times, two when my town got large enough.Right, I should talk about your giant floating hand. It floats. Picks up stuff, given that you have enough influence/essence. Other abilities include launching fireballs from heaven, calling lighting storms to bring rain, and really horrifying lighting (picture having a wall with a large of amount of zombies on the other side of it, then picture said wall getting blown up by lightning. Begin to cry because you've just been overrun by zombies.) call an earthquake that is equally terrifying, call a holy golem which needs a serious buff because it's far more expensive than what it could be used for, regrow entire forests and large amounts of food (which while they may say they are different vegetables, they are really and honestly carrots with different colors), banish your enemies, recall all resources, nomads, and stray villagers to your town center, warp things in and out of limbo (your global map storage), and even disolve any and all living and once living things for more essence. Oh, did I mention your villagers tend to freak out by your hand?Most importantly, you will fail, and that is okay. You will simply doom this world thus erasing any and all evidence of failure, and start again."
,Not Recommended,328080,24377218,"Posted: 17 July, 2016",all,Fluff-Kevlar,"I like RPC, I really do. At the moment there's not much to it, however. If you like building villages, micro-managing resources and villager needs, RPC has a few good things going for it, but there's also a lot holding it back, including the word ""castle"".It's tough; really tough actually, and if you screw up, you pretty much have to make a new profile to try again, you can't just pick a different area on the map. This is a minor annoyance given that you can easily screw yourself over, especially while just learning the game.I like that there's enemies to defend your castle against, but they -easily- overwhelm most defenses, and at the moment, the only way to defend is tower-defense-like mazes you have to build, where half of the towers are pretty much useless. I found the fire towers to draw way too much power to be useful and the rock towers near useless since they have to be out in the open,(can't be behind walls) right where enemies can easily swarm it, making the point of it, to roll a rock down a line of enemies, useless. Real castles didn't work this way, they had gates, moats, walls you could sit on and shoot down, etc. I really wish there was more ""castle"" in this game. There really isn't, it's more akin to Retro-Pixel Villages.It's a fun little game, I like the aesthetic, and I like most of the resource managment and crafting system, but I'm gonna wait and come back to it later when/if/hopefully they add more ""castle"" elements like walls with gates and such, I'm tired of making mazes and getting overwhelmed, and when more later-game content comes in. Very nice so far though! I will revisit and re-review it in the future."
