,Recommended,328080,34472788,Posted: 24 August,all,☭ Ficklestein ☭,"No ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t review. Straight to the chase. It's $10. Get it. Review: 40+ hours in. I've played Caesar III, Zeus, Pharoah, SimCity, Rollercoaster Tycoon, Gnomoria, The Guild II, and numerous other great management, defense, citybuilding games out there, even Banished (not recommended, see my review for it). I adore this genre and this game easily fits in with the best of them. It's very similar to Gnomoria but with an easier interface and on a larger scale.I've mostly played this on Survival. Great balance between risks/dangers and development. You WILL build a beautiful village/city with 500+ individual semi-autonomous villagers even, but you will also HAVE to feed them, quench their thirst, gear them, and allocate them to their roles and tasks as efficiently as possible to thwart nightly monster raids.That is, you will build a village and you will constantly be fighting for survival. Even at larger populations, you will still have to find a way to feed your village when your farms stop growing in the winter and enough clean water in the hot summer. Gear them up to fight off the monsters. Build defence towers from a limited pool of resources and building slots. Build walls to funnel the monsters through them.It will be a real challenge and unlike Banished, there is a real risk.Moreover, there's a world map with multiple locations to build villages. You can move resources and material from one village to another with your godly abilities.Game's still in Early Access. Could use improvements and additions such as trade. Dev says he's working on them. We'll see. So far, beautiful game as it is. And for $10? Absolutely recommended. No second thoughts."
76561198027106612,Recommended,328080,14293806,"Posted: 2 February, 2015",all,Star Adept,"I'll do my best to keep this review updated as the game progresses. (2/1/2015 - Current Ver: Indev12c, Indev13 roadmap announced)I'm recommending this, but I have a few caveats before I get to my review. If you're expecting a game that is 100% or even 80% realized as of (2/1/2015) then you probably haven't had much experience with Early Access and you probably shouldn't buy this game YET. Or if the feedback-and-support thing doesn't appeal to you, the $15 pricetag might seem a bit steep. Even then, if you're afraid of vaporware (I know I am), read the store page thoroughly as Ray (the dev) has done his best to put your fears to rest. Still mistrusting? I'm here for ya, or go to the website (or any of the links provided on the store page) and form your own opinionOfficial Website(main website link on store page seems to be broken). I know it's some extra effort than you would normally spend, but Ray is very active on his official forums and he will certainly answer any questions regarding his vision and the current state of development before you make a decision on purchasing.That said, I feel with the risk of vaporware and rushed products, opinion on the dev in an Early Access review is just as important as the game itself and I'll address that with my opinion first. If you don't care, scroll down and read the game portion. I'll remove this once the game goes Full-Access.Review of Indie Developer Raymond Doerr(scroll down for game review)This man has earned my respect among a slew of Indie ""Developers"" (Opportunists) that started with Minecraft (Jeb had made a lot of promises like our Alpha/Beta contributions entitling us to free Xbox copies before it was so popular -- didn't happen) and continues to this day with practically every Early Access game on Steam. So much so I've learned to type the simple little word ""dev"" with a bit of spite in my mental voice. Ray is not that man. While this is an opinion, and one I cannot garuntee in the future, I very strongly feel this way. Just talk to him, you'll see.Little things like his naming of his updates Indev12-13 versus 0.12.02 (this is no race to the magic 1.0! it's just a progress report) to his efforts to ask/require your input and support when so many people are so rightfully afraid to give it through an otherwise legitimate manner set him apart.When I was younger, Independently-Developed games were practically non-existent. To be a Beta Tester, you had to send in a resume to a big name company and you had to be hired, it was a job, before your voice ever mattered in the gaming world. I have a job so that's not an option, but through Ray and his SixtyGig Games (and with $15) my voice is heard. That is what Early Access, Independently-Developed games, and Raymond Doerr is all about.(had to be cut short for the actual game review, the lengthy praise is warranted though, I f-ing hate vaporware and the only way around it are honest reviews)Review of Retro-Pixel CastlesCurrent Version: Indev12c(Pro/Con lists are not my style, hope you like to read)InfluencesOn the Steam Store Page, the game is marked as having several noticable influences, but in its current version, I mainly  agree with three of them, and I'll try to break them down.Dwarf Fortress:This is the most obvious influence in my opinion (and also the closest game to ever touch upon what I want in a DF-like game), You have practically zero control over your villagers. You can place buildings to be constructed when your villagers get to it (although in a generally predictable manner), set resource harvesting tasks, and assign free (random) villagers to work at certain buildings. That's about it for control right now, and where most of the DF influence stops. P.S. ""Losing is Fun!"" theme is well-intact in Retro-Pixel Castles.Banished:You start the game on whatever map you choose with nothing but a bunch of villagers and are free to choose where you place your Village Center (required before you can build anything else and serves as radial zone for where you can place other buildings at first, so choose wisely!), unless someone (or you!) has made a map where the Village Center was already placed (you only get one, this ain't no 4x). Also, when you build your first farm, you have to collect wild food (carrots only, so far) before they can start growing them in the farm (this is a one-time deal, a working farm can populate a new one). While it is ultimately a village sim and has buildings, food/energy requirements, I'd end the tracable influences to Banished there.Tower Defense:This is a big one, as it encompasses the actual challenge of the game. I spend most of my time on Peaceful, because I'm a casual grow-and-love city builder type gamer, but this is one of the rare few games where I'll switch off peaceful and play the regular game because A) Peaceful at this stage is -super- low on content and extremely easy being locked on Day 1 difficulty (you really only need/will ever use 2-4 of the available building types) B) Instead of devoting my city to raising a military, in Tower Defense style, your buildings do most of the work for you (your villagers will fight mobs, dumbly, and you will lose a lot of them, but that's the point! ""Losing is Fun!""). Also, currently, you get to have one save, per mode, per map, per profile (you really only need one profile, unless you have a family or RL friends -scoff-) so I can come back to my peaceful cities when I want. So far (more buildings planned in the next update, expect this to change), the only offensive building is a Fire Tower (you can also build walls for defense/mob funneling) which will TD-style automatically fire at mobs close enough. All living things die in a burst of pixelated blood and green ""essence"" which serves as mana/power for your Fire Tower (and an Essence Collector, which is essentially a battery for the Fire Tower). Every day that you survive, the rate that mobs appear increases, and so the difficulty.Most of the game and its mechanics are covered above.Atmosphere:Pixels!:At this point, you either love pixel-art or hate it. If you love it, this game does it very well. There's even an option to smooth out some of the pixel animation like essence flowing to an Essence Collector/Fire Tower(which looks gorgeous and well-fantasy-themed even for pixels), but I like pixels so I haven't even bothered. I'll edit this next time I go into the game and look (which may not be til the next update).Music/Sound:Music is a nice, calming fantasy-like tune that fits well into the pixel-art world. I've never had to turn it down or off after several hours, but that's really all I have to say about it, as I tend to not notice game music anyways. Sounds come mainly from birth/death of villagers and are just a quick happy or sad tune that fits with the music-style.Maps:You can make your own maps!Saved in whatever, and however many, folders you'd like. Ray is currently not very focused on (or very impressive at - sorry man) making maps for the game himself, which brings me to a special point.If you buy Early Access and you make a good map and post it on his forum, Ray may add your map to the game before final release!This is, as far as it stands now, an Early-Access-Only feature. I've seen those threads pop up, and I've seen maps get added, and updated. Be a real contributor to the game!Maps are 1-z level (no digging down DF fans, these are humans!) but give a vague impression of depth as dense resources appear ""taller"" than their regular counterparts and is a nice touch to the aesthetic without complicated mechanics needed.Currently, Ray is experimenting with map size in an effort to reduce code/program efficiency, so if you get in now, there might be changes."
