76561197979511633,Recommended,328080,29886660,Posted: 12 February,all,BYE!!! BYE BYE!!!,"Pros:-Love the pixel art style of the game-Tower defense aspects set it apart a bit from other Dwarf Fortress-likes, combat is an extremely core part of the game and that's not a bad thing at all.-Totally reasonable price. I got it on sale for $5, but even the default price of $10 is reasonable. I bought this less than a week ago as of this review and I already have over 24 hours put into it. The dev is also extremely active so I'm confident in the game's future.-Plenty of content already - a lot of resources, items, and buildings to create.Cons:-Slow pace. The dev has already expressed he has no plans to include a 2x/3x speed option like in games such as Banished or RimWorld, however he will be including a Haste spell to speed your workers up. From what I can tell, this spell will really only be truly useful in the very first 2 or 3 days, because after that you will want to save your mana to blow up enemy spawns. So I don't think that the Haste spell will really solve much. The dev has stated higher speeds would be unnecessary because of the pace of the game, but I find myself with tons of downtime at every stage of the game. If it is a problem of implementation, I can understand, but I see no reason why an optional 2x or 3x speed button shouldn't be added.-Difficulty does not continue to scale. Now that I've done a few runs and I have a strategy for early-mid game, I'm completely ironclad and unstoppable by around day 11. More enemies will probably need to be added (remember you can always do resizes/recolors of existing sprites, nobody gets too upset about that as long as it's not rampant) that can add to more of a late game challenge.-Defense is pretty easy. All you need to do is make a large perimeter for your base and include a single choke point. Because of the enemy AI, they will walk across the entire map just to get to that choke point. I would recommend adding a certain distance threshold for enemies so that if they have to walk a certain distance to get around a wall, they will instead attack the nearest wall. This will force players to maintain multiple points of defense instead of one easily defended chokepoint.Misc suggestions:Quarries like in Banished - on rock floor areas, maybe you could add a building that allows villagers to mine a set amount of rock and iron from a 10x10 spot or however large you'd deem it. My reasoning for this is that I often run out of stone toward the end of the second year, and this would add another way of getting some. It's basically like they're hollowing out that part of the ground.Diagonal roads - just make it so that when roads are connected to another road by only the corner you use a particular diagonal-road sprite. This is for both aesthetic reasons and because diagonal roads are obviously useful given by their automatic creation by the NPCs' pathing.Alternative food sources - domesticated animals, fish.Towers that induce status effects (slow, bleed, decrease armor, etc)"
76561197963650004,Not Recommended,328080,31733649,Posted: 13 May,all,kurple,"Disappointing. The videos and previews of the game are VERY different from the current state of the game. It is no longer the brutal survival simulator that I saw on youtube and on steam. Monsters are very nonaggresive and doctile preferring to stay near their nests and wander around doing nothing. During night time very few monsters bother coming over to destroy my village. And the fights are definitely not as thrilling as the videos made them out to be. There's just one monster with crazy amounts of HP instead of multiple monsters with smaller amounts of HP. This change made the game very...bland. The tower defense aspect of the game isn't very exciting either. Due to the constant restraints of the ""building limit"" you have to keep upgrading your homebase in order to build more towers. And after you get ""permission"" from the ministry of labours your building sites are constantly blocked by tree ""stumps"". When you mine a resource like a tree or a rock for example they leave behind a little ""stump"" that blocks any construction on where the resource used to be. Now I think I understand why this was implimented. It was probably implemented to ""protect"" the player from over harvesting resources so that way they always have a ""stump"" to go back to for more wood, crystals, food etc. What I find troubling about this philosophy is that it is counter intuitive of the philosophy of the game. What I thought the game was about was SURVIVAL, not the forever sand box. The problem with this is two fold: one there already is a survival and sandbox modes so the over arching ""protection"" from the devs to prevent overharvesting goes beyond what the modes imply; players are being handheld in survival mode and it feels...boring. The second problem is that there is no ""end game"" for sandbox right now (neither for survival) so it doesn't matter.Over all I thought this game was going to be breakneck difficulty like dwarffortress, but instead it was a hand-holding, carebear boredom. I like difficulty and I found none here. I was so bored I left my base to run for a couple of real life hours without me and when I came back it was just fine (except for a few people gone missing).If you wanted a care-bear experience with mild tower defense you found the game. If you expected dwarffortress with some cool tower defense aspect to it, you won't find it here."
