rts were completely free and the third part came to steam without any early access thing and for a decent price.I personally experience it as a ripoff if the content of the game is developed in the (paid) early access since that is not what it is about. The early access is for fine-tuning the game and get some feedback from the comunity. Its about giving the game its last 5-10% not its last 50%.Sorry that all of my all of my bottled-up displeasure about seemingly half-ready games got into this review. I hope that you get point."
,Not Recommended,328080,34600090,Posted: 30 August,all,TseiCo,"I mentioned in the review that the game crashed for me and the dev contacted me (see comments) within an hour or so. I know indie devs fear negative reviews like the plague, but it's still nice to get instant help. But seeing that the game was released into EA in october 2014, it kinda left me with a feeling that the dev is more concerned about the negative reviews than finishing the game. Now I just bought the game and haven't been observing the pace of the development, so I might be completely off with that (and I hope I am). I also took a quick glance at the steam forums and it seemed like the dev was actually active there too (which is surprisingly rare).Thoughts about the actual gameplay after 10 hours:+The pace of the game seems good. Doesn't require reflexes like a RTS would, but also doesn't make you just sit and wait too much.+In general it shows potential and implies that it has depth and replay value.+For the most part the UI is clear and easy to use.+-The lack of in-game tutorial. There is a button for ""Watch a tutorial video"" and the game gives you some general tips along the way, but they help very little.-The game offers too little information about things like how many buidlings you need to have in order to have your town survive (farms for food, wells or rain catchers for water etc).-The time for pixel graphics has come and gone. It actually gets extremely blurry if you zoom in even a little bit (why does it even allow you to do this?).-The villagers' AI is sometimes bugged and not knowing what their priority is in performing different tasks takes a lot of the fun out of the game.-Some of the buttons on the UI (assigning villagers to different buildings for example) are WAY too small, considering the next point.-The mouse pointer moves like it's on a rubber band. The delay ain't that bad, but just enough that it actually gets really annoying to try and aim at some of the smaller buttons.It's these last two points that made my review negative. Feels like something that wouldn't bother a normal person, but some of the buttons are really small and the rubber banding mouse ain't helping.And in case anyone gets to read this before the fanboys downvote this into oblivion (as they do to all negative reviews): I'm not saying not to buy it. But I am suggesting to keep an eye on the development for a while before doing so."
