,Recommended,328080,22056366,"Posted: 25 March, 2016",all,{-o-} Baltazar,"Retro-Pixel Castles is an interesting game that seems to show great promise.How would I describe the game? I guess I would say that it's something of a god-sim mixed with a city-building sim. Nothing too outside the box, generally speaking.What else can I really say? My little men and women run about the world, mating and harvesting and mating some more (and stopping to chat all the damn time), and I continue to direct them to build stone walls, fire towers, and refining facilities. There's not much more to it at this point. However, that's due to the fact that the game is still in early access rather than any lack of vision on the part of the developers. I can see that there is a lot of room to grow in Retro-Pixel Castles and I have high hopes that the devs will continue to utilize that space.The tutorials cover most everything you will need to know (not everything, of course, but they're tutorials - not strategy guides. I feel like there should be some information left to the player to discover). It's not difficult to figure out how to get a thriving community up and running once you understand the basic build order.I guess that would be one of my main complaints about the game (and there aren't too many complaints I could actually list - see the end of the review for my short list): once you understand the basic build order of the game there isn't very much in the way of challenge with attaining a thriving community. It seems like the game is, so far, simple and easy. This can be changed further on in development, and I feel like with the addition of more content the challenge rating should rise decently.Since pro/con lists seem to be all the rage in reviews, I will use one now. This list is not exhaustive.Pros:+Easy to learn mechanics+Enjoyable and open-ended simulation+Pleasing graphical elements+Entertaining gameplayCons:-Soundtrack gets repetitive-It can be a bit of a hassle figuring out which unit is your villager and which is the monster in a large melee-Small amount of content at this point-Lack of effective late-game purpose (once I've built all the buildings and made my havens safe for my townsfolk there isn't any reason to continue except to raise a large population in order to populate more areas of the map)I want to make a note that I feel like all of the cons so listed are easily fixed and I have a good feeling that the devs are either currently working towards those goals or will soon begin to do so.I won't waste any time attempting to offer my thoughts as to how to fix said cons - this is simply a review.Anyway, without going on too long (too late) I would have to say this: if you're a fan of god sims or city building sims then you should definitely keep an eye on this game. With a few more updates I think it could easily become a mainstay of your gaming repertoire. With a full complement of content I feel that Retro-Pixel Castles could be something great."
